nolo—auditorem. Both the Romans and Greeks preferred to negative the principal verb where we should join the negative particle with the Inf. as in the well-known instances of πορθ, οὐ φημί z so here nolo—ath'morem instead of volo—non adiutorem. If the subordinate sentence is composed of two members, one negative, the other affirmative, the negative verb is still retained, the corresponding affirmative being suggested in thought before the second clause, as here nolo suggests volo before auditorem (sc. existimes me mah-se).
